<protolog id="rid.3887_nm.9751" type="description" xmlns="http://namesforlife.com/ns/protolog" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://namesforlife.com/ns/protolog file:/C:/NamesforLife/workspace/namesforlife-schema/protolog.xsd"><organism doi="10.1601/nm.9751" rank="genus">Leadbetterella</organism><reference id="rid.3887"><citation citation-type="journal"><authors><person-name><surname>Weon</surname><given-names>H.Y.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Kim</surname><given-names>B.Y.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Kwon</surname><given-names>S.W.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Park</surname><given-names>I.C.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Cha</surname><given-names>I.B.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Tindall</surname><given-names>B.J.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Stackebrandt</surname><given-names>E.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Trüper</surname><given-names>H.G.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Go</surname><given-names>S.J.</given-names></person-name></authors><article-title>Leadbetterella byssophila gen. nov., sp. nov., isolated from cotton-waste composts for the cultivation of oyster mushroom.</article-title><year>2005</year><volume>55</volume><issue>6</issue><fpage>2297</fpage><lpage>2302</lpage><source id="117">International Journal of Systematic and Evolutionary Microbiology</source><abbrev>Int J Syst Evol Microbiol</abbrev><issn>1466-5026</issn><essn>1466-5034</essn><pub-id pub-id-type="doi">10.1099/ijs.0.63741-0</pub-id><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">16280486</pub-id></citation></reference><content><p class="title"><s>Description of <em>Leadbetterella</em> gen. nov.</s></p><p class="etymology"><s><em>Leadbetterella</em> (Lead.bet.te.rel′la. N.L. fem. n. <em>Leadbetterella</em> in honour of Dr Edward R. Leadbetter, who studied bacteria belonging to the CFB group).</s></p><p class="description"><s>Cells are strictly aerobic, Gram-negative, non-motile and non-gliding rods.</s><s>Oxidase and catalase are positive.</s><s>Flexirubin-type pigments are present.</s><s>Several carbohydrates are used as sole carbon sources.</s><s>Aesculin, gelatin, starch and tyrosine are degraded.</s><s>Major fatty acids are C<sub>16 : 1</sub><em>ω</em>7<em>c</em>/iso-C<sub>15 : 0</sub> 2-OH, iso-C<sub>15 : 0</sub>, iso-C<sub>15 : 0</sub> 2-OH/C<sub>16 : 1</sub><em>ω</em>7<em>c</em>, iso-C<sub>17 : 0</sub> 3-OH and C<sub>16 : 0</sub>.</s><s>Respiratory quinone is menaquinone MK-7.</s><s>The type species is <em>Leadbetterella byssophila</em>.</s></p></content></protolog>